An ovigerous 

P. planissimum

from Raoul I. reported above (
21.9 mm
x 
23.8 mm
) carried around 2000 very small eggs (diameter = 
0.30–0.35 mm
). As might be expected for a species with such a wide distribution, it is likely that the larval stages spend a long period in the plankton during which they are transported considerable distances. The eggs are carried in two distinct clutches (left and right) in the narrow brood chamber beneath the flattened abdomen. The gonopores are not operculate.
